The way interep works is that once you sign up you are able to post. But your anonimity set is the number of people who have signed up.

I am working on something similar but in a slightly simpler manner:
- when posting anonymously, a hash is derived using the logic "sign(messageId, privateKey)"
- the sha256(hash) becomes the private key of the post, known only to original poster. The corresponding pubkey is embedded to the post payload
- when op reply to the post, we just need to check if "sha256(sign(messageId, privatekey)).getPublicKey()" matches the one embedded in the post

The private key uses to sign the message id comes from one of two places:
- for wallet user, they already have a ECDSA keypair when registering with the protocol 
- for anon user, their private key can be derived using the logic "sha256(identityNullifer, identitySecret)"

src: https://g11power.medium.com/kate-commitments-in-eth-9cbcb0174732
Kate commitments encode data as polynomials and commit to this data by opening the polynomial at a secret  point, the secret point is decided during a trusted setup.
